# Changelog Maintenance

`CHANGELOG.md` at the repo root tracks notable changes. Keep it in sync with the code.

## When to update

Add an entry for any change that affects users:

- New constructor kwargs or `reset()` options
- API renames or removals (public exports, `info` field names, etc.)
- New or removed environments (`Procedural-FrozenLake-v1`, …)
- Changes to output/metric format or reward behavior
- Bug fixes that change observable behavior

## When NOT to update

Skip the changelog for:

- Internal refactors with no observable effect
- Test-only changes
- Doc typo fixes (no behavior change)

## Format

Always add new work to `## [Unreleased]` — never add new entries to an already dated release block.
Use these sub-sections (omit any that don't apply):

```markdown
## [Unreleased]

### Added
- ...

### Changed
- ...

### Removed
- ...

### Fixed
- ...
```

## On version bump

When `version` in `pyproject.toml` is changed, promote `[Unreleased]` to the new version with today's date:

```markdown
## [x.y.z] - YYYY-MM-DD
```

Leave a fresh empty `## [Unreleased]` above it.

## Before finishing

For every implementation task, explicitly check whether the change is user-visible.

- If yes, verify `CHANGELOG.md` has a matching `## [Unreleased]` entry before the final response.
- If no, mention internally that the changelog was intentionally skipped because the change is test-only, internal-only, or a doc typo.
- Do not consider the task complete if a public API, behavior, environment, output format, reward behavior, or documented feature changed without an `[Unreleased]` changelog entry.
